Horace here predicts the glory and immortality of his name. And, with the true spirit of a poet, he imagines himself already as- suming the form and faculties of a swan, and soaring above the earth, over which he is about to tolie his aeria] flight. Aa he will leave the humble abodes cimon, so he will shake off “ this morta] coil,” and cease to be an object of human sympathy or sorrow. He wishes not for the empty honora of a burial, nor the waste of useless tears on hia account, since he shall not die.
